---
// Section 2 — Agitation
// "You've already tried this" — names the two broken options (databases + agencies)
// that the buyer has already attempted. Direct-address, diagnostic tone.
---

<section
  id="agitation"
  class="py-32 md:py-40 px-6 md:px-10 lg:px-16"
  style="background: var(--color-bg);"
>
  <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto">
    <!-- Section heading -->
    <h2
      data-reveal
      class="font-serif leading-[1.02] tracking-tight max-w-3xl"
      style="
        color: var(--color-ink);
        font-size: clamp(2rem, 5.2vw, 4.25rem);
      "
    >
      You've already <em style="font-style: italic;">tried</em> this.
    </h2>

    <!-- Intro lede -->
    <p
      data-reveal
      data-reveal-delay="1"
      class="mt-10 md:mt-12 max-w-2xl text-lg md:text-xl leading-relaxed"
      style="color: var(--color-ink-muted);"
    >
      Most small-to-mid-sized companies doing creator marketing today face two options.
      Both are broken.
    </p>

    <!-- Two-column breakdown -->
    <div
      class="mt-16 md:mt-24 grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-14 md:gap-0"
    >
      <!-- Column 1: Databases -->
      <div
        data-reveal
        data-reveal-delay="2"
        class="md:pr-10 lg:pr-16 md:border-r"
        style="border-color: var(--color-rule);"
      >
        <h3
          class="font-serif leading-[1.08] tracking-tight"
          style="
            color: var(--color-ink);
            font-size: clamp(1.625rem, 2.8vw, 2.25rem);
          "
        >
          Databases ask you to be your own agency.
        </h3>
        <p
          class="mt-6 md:mt-8 text-base md:text-lg leading-relaxed"
          style="color: var(--color-ink-muted);"
        >
          Creator databases sell you a filtered list and expect you to do the rest:
          pitch every creator, qualify the fit, negotiate the deal, coordinate the
          placement, measure the outcome. What you get is a lead list, not a campaign.
          Every hour of filtering is an hour you don't have.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Column 2: Agencies -->
      <div
        data-reveal
        data-reveal-delay="3"
        class="md:pl-10 lg:pl-16"
      >
        <h3
          class="font-serif leading-[1.08] tracking-tight"
          style="
            color: var(--color-ink);
            font-size: clamp(1.625rem, 2.8vw, 2.25rem);
          "
        >
          Agencies ask you to pay like you're an enterprise.
        </h3>
        <p
          class="mt-6 md:mt-8 text-base md:text-lg leading-relaxed"
          style="color: var(--color-ink-muted);"
        >
          Traditional creator marketing agencies run on retainers sized for
          eight-figure marketing budgets. If yours is smaller, you're either priced
          out — or treated as a secondary account while the agency's real clients
          get the attention. The retainer gets paid whether the campaign converts
          or not.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Closing line — serif italic, reads as editorial aside -->
    <p
      data-reveal
      data-reveal-delay="4"
      class="mt-20 md:mt-28 max-w-2xl font-serif leading-snug"
      style="
        color: var(--color-ink-subtle);
        font-style: italic;
        font-size: clamp(1.25rem, 1.75vw, 1.625rem);
      "
    >
      Most companies in the middle run sporadic one-off campaigns, hire a freelancer,
      or quietly give up on the channel. None of it compounds.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>
